
[1]wield

   WIELD, v.t. [L. The primary sense of power and strength is to stretch
   or strain.]

   1. To use with full command or power, as a thing not too heavy for the
   holder; to manage; as, to wield a sword; to wield the scepter.

   Part wield their arms, part curb the foaming steed.

   2. To use or employ with the hand.

   Nothing but the influence of a civilized power could induce a savage to
   wield a spade.

   3. To handle; in an ironical sense.

   Base Hungarian wight, wilt thou the spigot wield?

   To wield the scepter, to govern with supreme command.
